# Overview

These are rules for writing CSS code.

## File structure

Here is example of the file structure, the individual css files here are just examples, we wont need all of them.

src/web/css
├── base - resets default styles for type, headers etc that applies to elements in all pages.
│   ├── main.css - styles for html, body, p, etc.
│   └── headers.css - styles for headers
├── modules - contains css for individual modules
│   ├── thumb.css - styles for the track thumbnail
│   └── headers.css - styles for headers
├── states - contains css for state class similar to Tailwind CSS: tm-3, bp-4, cl-red-500, etc.
│   ├── colors.css - styles for colors
│   ├── margins.css - styles for margins
│   ├── paddings.css - styles for positions
│   ├── width.css - styles for display
│   └──flex.css - styles for flex
└── app.css - main stylesheet included from html layout, it imports other css with @import directive.


## Code style

* CSS should be flat, no cascading, or nesting.
* For common styles, like margins, colors, padding, using Tailwind style class from `states` dir: `tm-3`, `bp-4`, `cl-red-500`, etc.
* For styling individual parts of HTML use modules locates in `modules` dir, use case like `TrackThumb`.
* Module inner elements will start with the same module and separated with dashes: `TrackThumb-Image`, `TrackThumb-Link`.
